# Decisions

Layer-3 knowledge: durable decisions the user has made. Always in context. These are the load-bearing commitments — the assistant should treat them as standing rules unless the user revises them.

> **This is a template.** Copy it to your content vault as `kb/decisions.md` and replace the placeholder entries with real ones. The method repo never holds the real file.

Each entry follows the format:

```
## <Decision title>
- **Date:** <YYYY-MM-DD>
- **Status:** decided | proposed | revisited
- **Last verified:** <YYYY-MM-DD>
- **Expires:** <YYYY-MM-DD or never>
- **Source:** <ADR / issue / conversation / manual>
- **Scope:** <person / org / team / project — what this decision is *about*>

<short body — what was decided + the load-bearing reason.>
```

The `Scope` field names the referent the decision applies to (e.g., `Nuro`, `BADAS team`, `Nexar`). It is what makes context-dependent decisions retrievable from the always-in-context layer — without it, a heading like "NYC added as fourth priority geography" can't be matched to its real subject (a Nuro deal). For decisions that apply broadly (e.g., a company-wide policy), use the operating org name (`Nexar`). Drift detection (per [#135](https://github.com/acardote/personal-assistant-ultra/issues/135)) routes newly-harvested memory against decisions sharing the same Scope.

This file is for **your** decisions — strategy commitments, policy rules, persistent priorities. Method-level architectural decisions (about the assistant itself) live in `docs/adr/*.md` in the method repo.

---

## <Decision Title — e.g., "Adopted thin integration spine for Q2 2026">

- **Date:** <YYYY-MM-DD>
- **Status:** decided
- **Last verified:** <YYYY-MM-DD>
- **Expires:** <YYYY-MM-DD or 'never (revisit if <criterion>)'>
- **Source:** <pointer to a real artifact: a Granola note, an email thread, a doc>
- **Scope:** <referent — person, org, team, or project this is about>

<short body: what was decided + the load-bearing reason. Concrete numbers,
deadlines, named owners. The assistant treats this as ground truth when
answering related questions. The drift detector (#135) periodically checks
newly-harvested memory against this decision and surfaces material
contradictions for your review.>

